Managing a business as an introverted creative who is very private shouldn't be complicated, and yet, it sometimes is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with big (and diabolical) technology companies using extraverted techniques. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service checked out, be available 24/7, respond to questions with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
01/03/2024
It's a transition year for me.
I do not want to feed large technology companies with my money, my data, and my energy. Nor do I want coaches who have a single solution for extroverts that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my activities while fighting against the idea I've long believed in, that things must be done a certain way in order to succeed.
Wish me luck!
I have already completed the first steps.
I left Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday, and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to a Europe-based CRM for better GDPR compliance, and I will be migrating my activity over the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX to Proton and I'm now fully taking advantage of SPF, DKIM, and DMAR, without having to pay Google for basic email address verification.
03/03/2024
